28.799999999999997px;"><strong>Full MAGA or Mere Sycophancy?</strong></h3>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table class=3D"c4" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspaci=
ng=3D"0" role=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspa=
ce:0pt;word-break:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"r" style=3D"padding-=
bottom:32px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;In=
ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;">What are the offenses, exactly, that so infuriated Marcus and Bar=
on and Barr and
Shipley, and Pulitzer Prize winner <strong>David Maraniss</strong>, and so =
on? What interventions by the owner and publisher are damaging the <em>Post=
</em>=E2=80=99s sacred mission, and making it so untenable for these vetera=
ns to stay? (Maraniss remains on the payroll, but refuses to write). What s=
ycophantic display has convinced them that the <em>Post </em>is now turning=
 a blind eye to Trump=E2=80=99s transgressions or, as the Beast put it, goi=
ng =E2=80=9CFull MAGA=E2=80=9D?<br/><br/>Marcus lays out a chronology of
now-familiar infractions, reliable grist for the alarmist <strong>Folkenfli=
k</strong> mill: Bezos=E2=80=99s decision to kill the paper=E2=80=99s <stro=
ng>Kamala Harris </strong>endorsement; his post-election embrace of Trump; =
the Mar-a-Lago dinner; Amazon=E2=80=99s million-dollar donation to the inau=
guration, and its in-kind $40 million contribution via a ludicrously expens=
ive licensing deal for a doc about <strong>Melania</strong>. The company al=
so recently picked up the rights to <em>The Apprentice</em>. Closer to
home: Shipley=E2=80=99s decision to kill a cartoon by Pulitzer Prize winner=
 <strong>Ann Telnaes</strong> that depicted Bezos and other tech executives=
 genuflecting to Trump=E2=80=94=E2=80=9Can instance of obeying in advance,=
=E2=80=9D per Marcus. (Telnaes subsequently resigned and <a href=3D"https:/=
/email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dWalVRWHZZb3=
hlN3lwcWlQNFQ2MD0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9hbm50ZWxuYWVzLnN1YnN0YWNrLmNvbS9wL=
3doeS1pbS1xdWl0dGluZy10aGUtd2FzaGluZ3Rvbi1wb3N0P3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1Jbit0aGUr=
Um9vbSstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODMlMkYxMiUyRjI1JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9SW4=
rVGhlK1Jvb20rLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgzJTJGMTIlMkYyNSUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9tZWRpdW=
09ZW1haWxfYWN0aW9uXHUwMDI2dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jdXN0b21lci5pb1x1MDAyNnV0bV90ZXJtP=
WY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImludGVybmFsIjoiZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwibGlu=
a19pZCI6MjExODM1OX0/51230125d4bbb1c76dd604c25696cc2882d9dbcf8b032249540c1ee=
6d85f9f80" style=3D"text-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;">published</a>=
 her own =E2=80=9CWhy I=E2=80=99m Quitting=E2=80=9D treatise on Substack.)<=
br/><br/>There=E2=80=99s more: A critical article about Bezos=E2=80=99s
Opinions mandate from media critic <strong>Erik Wemple</strong>, which neve=
r ran; and finally, Lewis=E2=80=99s rejection of Marcus=E2=80=99s own colum=
n, which, she was told, did =E2=80=9Cnot pass the =E2=80=98high bar=E2=80=
=99 required for the <em>Post </em>to write about itself=E2=80=94a message =
relayed to her by deputy Opinions editor <strong>Mary Duenwald</strong>, si=
nce Lewis himself refused a meeting. (Presumably, Wemple=E2=80=99s submissi=
on didn=E2=80=99t clear that bar, either.) At one point, Marcus invoked the
frog-in-the-simmering-pot metaphor. And, sure, framed as she and Baron and =
Barr have structured it, these moves <em>do</em> look like the green shoots=
 of a conspiracy, the start of the slippery slope toward a <em>Post </em>th=
at functions like <em>Pravda</em>.<br/><br/>Alas, there are some rather obv=
ious flaws to the argument, as anyone who reckons with the actual product m=
ight be quick to identify. First, the <em>Post</em> newsroom=E2=80=99s post=
ure toward Trump and his administration has not wavered
<em>at all</em>. Indeed, its coverage of <strong>Elon Musk</strong>=E2=80=
=99s Department of Government Efficiency, from the internal palace intrigue=
 to the real-world ramifications, has been notably comprehensive and aggres=
sive. Meanwhile, any cursory review of the <em>Post </em>website, at any ti=
me of day, reveals a newsroom that has not shied away from holding the pres=
ident to account for empty promises, misguided policies, or bad poll number=
s. (Its congressional coverage is relatively lackluster, of
course, which is why Lewis continues to consider a Punchbowl acquisition.)<=
br/><br/>None of that should be surprising, since Bezos has never made any =
attempt to interfere with the newsroom. After a dozen years of mostly hands=
-off ownership, he has now chosen to exert some influence over the op-ed pa=
ge, which is actually the typical territorial jurisdiction for media propri=
etors. Indeed, as <em>The Economist </em>editor-in-chief <strong>Zanny Mint=
on Beddoes
</strong><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1l=
EQUt2UktxclJLZ0dWalVRWHZZb3hlN3lwcWlQNFQ2MD0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm=
5ld3MvcG9kY2FzdF9lcGlzb2RlL2l0cy10aGUtZWNvbm9taXN0LXN0dXBpZC8_dXRtX2NhbXBha=
WduPUluK3RoZStSb29tKy0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MyUyRjEyJTJGMjUlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1f=
Y29udGVudD1JbitUaGUrUm9vbSstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODMlMkYxMiUyRjI1JTI5XHUwMDI=
2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMD=
I2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhY=
mQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjoyMTE2Mjg1fQ/e8159e1f90c17e17cfc88a359e39e7811da5c94e5=
a98ec6a7bba28a0fc6aa3b4" style=3D"text-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;"=
>told me</a> on <em>The Grill Room</em> this week: =E2=80=9CA proprietor of=
 a newspaper has every right to have the newspaper=E2=80=99s editorial page=
 follow whatever direction he or she wishes. That=E2=80=99s the sort of tra=
dition of American journalism.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>More stunning is how Bezos=
=E2=80=99s critics have sought to frame his Opinions mandate as some sort o=
f rightward lurch toward a pro-MAGA
worldview. In fact, his recent nudge toward a focus on personal liberties a=
nd free markets is analogous to the editorial philosophies of <em>The Econo=
mist</em>=E2=80=99s and <em>The Wall Street Journal</em>=E2=80=99s editoria=
l boards, both of which continue to be outspoken critics of Trump and his a=
dministration <em>precisely because of </em>their classical liberal worldvi=
ew. In <em>The Economist</em>=E2=80=99s telling, Trump is a dangerous and d=
isruptive Mafia don pouring gasoline on the American
economy. Meanwhile, <em>no</em> media organization has been nearly so effec=
tive at needling Trump as the <em>Journal </em>editorial board, which has r=
elentlessly taken Trump to task over his tariffs and recently called for le=
gal action against him on that issue. Would an opinion page like this reall=
y undermine the <em>Post</em>=E2=80=99s mission and erode its ability to ho=
ld power to account?<br/><br/>Indeed, personal liberties and free markets a=
re the true tenets of American entrepreneurship, an art form
that Bezos not only practiced but truly perfected. And while plenty of onlo=
okers have likened Bezos=E2=80=99s renovations at the <em>Post </em>to Musk=
=E2=80=99s chainsawing of the federal bureaucracy, this facile comparison m=
isses the point. Musk, for all his antics, is heavy-handedly and overbearin=
gly responding to a broad desire everywhere outside Washington to make the =
administrative state less financially burdensome. And, in many ways, Bezos=
=E2=80=99s decision to impose a new structure around some handsomely
compensated opinion professionals at a deficit-ridden organization reflects=
 a similar truth=E2=80=94they may be able to get a prime table at Cafe Mila=
no, but their work is invisible everywhere else.</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
