bottom:32px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;In=
ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;">If you strip away Bezos=E2=80=99s own sycophantic diplomacy=E2=80=
=94the inauguration, the Mar-a-Lago
pilgrimages, etcetera=E2=80=94and focus instead on the <em>Post</em>, itsel=
f, you=E2=80=99re left with instances in which the publisher or an editor i=
ntervened to block critical opinion pieces <em>not </em>about Trump, but ab=
out the paper=E2=80=99s owner. Against that, you would have to account for =
the many columns that <em>were</em> published, including one by <strong>Dan=
a Milbank </strong>that
<a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2Uktx=
clJLZ0dWalVRWHZZb3hlN3lwcWlQNFQ2MD0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud2FzaGluZ3R=
vbnBvc3QuY29tL29waW5pb25zLzIwMjUvMDIvMjgvZnJlZS1tYXJrZXRzLXBlcnNvbmFsLWxpYm=
VydGllcy10cnVtcC10aHJlYXQvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1Jbit0aGUrUm9vbSstK1NVQlNDUklCR=
VJTKyUyODMlMkYxMiUyRjI1JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9SW4rVGhlK1Jvb20rLStTVUJT=
Q1JJQkVSUyslMjgzJTJGMTIlMkYyNSUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWxfYWN0aW9uXHU=
wMDI2dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jdXN0b21lci5pb1x1MDAyNnV0bV90ZXJtPWY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZD=
EyYSIsImludGVybmFsIjoiZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwibGlua19pZCI6MjExODM2MH0/f=
089ace8ce07f2efea111befe8e42424d1ed19c1c920e3f09ad4355e3ad21400" style=3D"t=
ext-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;">identified</a> Trump as =E2=80=9Ct=
he single greatest threat to =E2=80=98personal liberties and free markets,=
=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D and another by <strong>Eugene Robinson</strong> that <a =
href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJ=
LZ0dWalVRWHZZb3hlN3lwcWlQNFQ2MD0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud2FzaGluZ3Rvbn=
Bvc3QuY29tL29waW5pb25zLzIwMjUvMDMvMDMva2F0aGFyaW5lLWdyYWhhbS13YXNoaW5ndG9uL=
XBvc3QtbGVnYWN5Lz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249SW4rdGhlK1Jvb20rLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgz=
JTJGMTIlMkYyNSUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9jb250ZW50PUluK1RoZStSb29tKy0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlM=
rJTI4MyUyRjEyJTJGMjUlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsX2FjdGlvblx1MDAyNnV0bV=
9zb3VyY2U9Y3VzdG9tZXIuaW9cdTAwMjZ1dG1fdGVybT1mNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJpb=
nRlcm5hbCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjIxMTgzNjF9/25c27783b3d=
c1d254c62cf9d494432cda8a8428ad947490d80205ee49ea3654d" style=3D"text-decora=
tion:underline;color:#d40000;">praised</a> Donald Graham=E2=80=99s mother,
<strong>Kay</strong>, for standing up to <strong>Nixon</strong> and, as Mar=
cus herself put it in <em>The New Yorker</em>, =E2=80=9C[evoking] an implic=
it comparison with the current owner and his relationship with Trump.=E2=80=
=9D<br/><br/>Should news proprietors set a =E2=80=9Chigh bar=E2=80=9D for r=
eceiving criticism from their own journalists? That=E2=80=99s a debate for =
another time, though I can understand why any of them, from <strong>Rupert =
</strong>to <strong>A.G.</strong>, would be reasonably miffed if they had t=
o face scrutiny
over their decisions in the pages of the <em>Journal </em>or the <em>Times<=
/em>, respectively. (You may have noticed that doesn=E2=80=99t tend to happ=
en.) In any event, that alone really has no bearing on whether the recent c=
hanges at <em>Post </em>Opinions are fundamentally damaging the paper=E2=80=
=99s journalism, or undermining its ability to report fairly and honestly o=
n Trump.<br/><br/>Anyway, the cacophony of outrage around Bezos=E2=80=99s m=
oves may have clouded another truth, as well. In moments like these, the
protests of revered elder statesmen=E2=80=94Marty, Ruth, etcetera=E2=80=94t=
end to garner a lot of press, and shape the narrative. But their antipathy =
toward Bezos is not at all fully representative of the actual sentiments in=
side the <em>Post </em>these days (nor are they =E2=80=9Cfurious,=E2=80=9D =
yet another thing the Beast headline got wrong). As one <em>Post </em>insid=
er told me, =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a cultural battle ongoing at the <em>P=
ost</em> between the old people and the new people. Seems pretty clear the =
new people will win,
you know, since they run the place and have the owner on their side.=E2=80=
=9D<br/><br/>Indeed, as I noted last week, these tormented cries from the o=
lds are likely the last=E2=80=94and most audible=E2=80=94gasps from the Gra=
ham-era nostalgics. To their credit, their protests are well-intentioned, a=
nd intended to preserve the integrity of an institution that has served an =
important function in American politics. But their arguments would be a lot=
 more convincing if they stopped acting like their owner was enabling the
downfall of democracy simply because=E2=80=94after buying the paper out of =
bankruptcy, infusing it with cash, upgrading its tech, tolerating hundreds =
of millions in annual losses and a lot of internal bullshit=E2=80=94he now =
wants <em>his </em>Opinions page to better align with some rather mundane a=
nd conventional principles.</p></div>
